<TITLE> Ex-minister Sadique dies at 73 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Jessore, Sept 9 (bdnews24.com)  Former education minister and Awami League leader ASHK Sadique died of heart failure Sunday morning at the age of 73. Sadique breathed his last at his constituency at Keshabpur, Jessore, according to his family members. He went to his constituency at Keshabpur Friday and suffered chest pain early Sunday. Doctors told bdnews24.com correspondent in Jessore that he had long been suffering from heart diseases. A member of the Awami League's advisory council and a former top bureaucrat, Sadique was elected lawmaker from Jessore-6 (Keshabpur) in 1996 and 2001. He was born in Jessore in 1934 to the family of his father Iyahia Sadique. Sadique went to America in 1954 after completing his honours degree in economics. He did his masters from Williams College and joined the Pakistan Civil Service in 1956. He served as sub-divisional officer in Nilphamari and Narayanganj from 1959 to 1961 and as deputy commissioner of Comilla in 1966. He was elected secretary to the then East Pakistan governor in 1967 and served the position until 1970. Sadique was secretary to Tajuddin Ahmed, the first prime minister of Bangladesh during the war of independence. On March 25, 1988, he joined the Awami League after resigning from civil service. Sadique was education minister in 1996-2001 Awami League government. He also became a member of the AL advisory council in December, 2002. He served as director of the National Institute of Public Administration, secretary to the ministries of industry, petroleum and mining and defence. He also worked as a specialist and local advisor to the UNIDO, a UN organisation. bdnews24.com/al/sk/su/wz
